1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,500
 My name is Benjamin Crockett, and I'm delighted to be here with my good friend, Fr. Kenny Eng.

2
00:00:04,500 --> 00:00:05,500
 Hi, Ben.

3
00:00:05,500 --> 00:00:13,500
 As we look at the emerging technology that is changing the way we think about work and education at the same time,

4
00:00:13,500 --> 00:00:17,500
 I think the Catholic vision of education is something different than maybe the secular model.

5
00:00:17,500 --> 00:00:23,500
 Yeah, so if we go back to the very founding of universities, right?

6
00:00:23,500 --> 00:00:31,500
 University of Bologna, right, 1088, or Oxford, Paris, Salamanca, right, the first universities.

7
00:00:31,500 --> 00:00:39,000
 The Catholic Church had a lot to do with the founding of universities, and universities were before cathedral schools, right?

8
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:43,000
 So what were the idea of university back then?

9
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:48,000
 Well, it's what we often call today liberal arts, right?

10
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:57,000
 So they're teaching the trivium, quadrivium, right, some grammar, logic, rhetoric, and then the sciences, right?

11
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:01,500
 You have mathematics, music, arithmetic, and then astronomy, right?

12
00:01:01,500 --> 00:01:04,000
 So there's a trivium, quadrivium.

13
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:09,500
 These are sciences that will make you free, hence the name liberal arts, right?

14
00:01:09,500 --> 00:01:15,000
 So arts, sciences that free a human person to what? To do the good.

15
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:23,000
 Freedom is not autonomy, right? Freedom is freedom, the ability to do the good I want to do, right?

16
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:25,000
 That's the idea of freedom.

17
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:30,000
 And if we fast forward to the 20th century, as you said, nowadays, people go to college without thinking, right?

18
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:35,000
 And then, okay, I just want to get a paper and that piece of paper that certifies that I've done this,

19
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:38,000
 and then I want to get a job, make money, etc.

20
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:48,000
 So the idea of education has been shifted towards, oh, this is learning something practical to do, right?

21
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:50,000
 It's like learning a trait.

22
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:55,000
 So it's no longer offering this freedom, right?

23
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:58,000
 At least in the idea of those studying.

24
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:08,000
 How can we learn from, let's say, twinitarian theology so we can focus our education in its original sense?

25
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:18,000
 So, you know, one of the greatest contributions of St. Thomas Aquinas was defining divine person as subsisting relation, right?

26
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:23,000
 So, what distinguishes the father from the son and the spirit, right?

27
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:26,000
 They're all, they're God, right?

28
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:29,000
 And they create together, right?

29
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:32,000
 So what distinguishes a person from the other two?

30
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:35,000
 And the father is paternity, right?

31
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:37,000
 He's father.

32
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:39,000
 He begot the son, right?

33
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:44,000
 And the son is distinguished by this relation of filiation towards the father.

34
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:49,000
 And the father and the son together spirate, right?

35
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:51,000
 Breathe the Holy Spirit.

36
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:54,000
 So it's the relation that distinguishes the divine persons.

37
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:04,000
 And we learned that in education, relation, relationships occupy central, central place as well.

38
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:07,000
 I had a professor back in Pamplona.

39
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:12,000
 He taught me moral theology, Jose Maria Pardo.

40
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:14,000
 He's a doctor as well.

41
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:18,000
 So he studied medicine before becoming a priest and theologian.

42
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:24,000
 I remember one thing he told us about his studies in medicine, right?

43
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:27,000
 Nowadays, he said, you have great books of medicine.

44
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:35,000
 You have books that connect you to the internet where you can find a three-dimensional illustration of a heart, right?

45
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:42,000
 So you have everything you want to study by yourself, to self-teach yourself, right?

46
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:43,000
 Medicine.

47
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:50,000
 And so presupposing that the students who do study medicine are the greatest students, right?

48
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:52,000
 The brightest there.

49
00:03:52,000 --> 00:04:01,000
 And what reasons do they have to come to class and listen to this doctor or professor talking about something they could learn elsewhere?

50
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:08,000
 So a classroom part has to be somehow novel, engaging, adding something.

51
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:11,000
 Otherwise, they would study better elsewhere.

52
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,000
 I mean, these are not lazy or slow students, right?

53
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:16,000
 They could do better elsewhere.

54
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:24,000
 So I think education here, like teaching at the university level, it's also offering something they can get elsewhere.

55
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:25,000
 And what is it, right?

56
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:26,000
 I've been thinking a lot about this.

57
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:33,000
 What is it that I, as an educator, as a teacher, lecturer, can offer that they couldn't obtain elsewhere?

58
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:35,000
 It's not the information.

59
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:36,000
 It's not the data.

60
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:39,000
 I think AI can give you better.

61
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:42,000
 I don't know if it's better, but give you data at least.

62
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:51,000
 The internet has a lot of information, but I can offer this human relationship that's not present on the internet.

63
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:54,000
 Yeah, and that wisdom of accompaniment.

64
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:57,000
 Like I think that possibility to make lifelong friendships.

65
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:00,000
 Like I think about my experience at the university.

66
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:03,000
 I studied at the University of California, Berkeley for my undergrad.

67
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:12,000
 And I would say that while the classes were excellent and the professors were wonderful, the most transformative aspects of my education were outside of class.

68
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:13,000
 It was those relationships.

69
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:17,000
 It was those first experiences with people and situations.

70
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:22,000
 It was, um, it was traversing that, that life experience of, you know, from 18 to 22.

71
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:23,000
 There's a lot of growth that happens.

72
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:24,000
 You figure out kind of who you are.

73
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:34,000
 And I feel like as much as I, I applaud online universities and, and, you know, ways for people to work and to study from home and to continue to be lifelong learners.

74
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:38,000
 I think that's something beautiful about, about this moment in time that people can go back to class.

75
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:46,000
 I think that you miss a big part of the university experience if you don't make a relationship with your, with your professors, with your mentors, with your tutors.

76
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:56,000
 Um, and I, and I'm, and I am worried about that because I think also that, that, that aspect of isolating yourself at home and just, you know, let's say getting the, the raw analytics or the raw data.

77
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:02,000
 Um, like I see that also with people wanting to do remote working while that's really comfortable and wonderful for a lot of things.

78
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:06,000
 I, I do think that that shared experience is part of what it means to be human.

79
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:07,000
 And I, and I am worried about that.

80
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:15,000
 And I, and I think that that kind of spirals into all the other issues, you know, we, we look at when, when you mentioned, you know, uh, attention deficit.

81
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:23,000
 Um, the ability to really work in a quiet space, like in a library and read a book for a period of time and really like highlight and read that.

82
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:32,000
 Like, I feel like communication and relationships are things that, that the current younger generations are, are going to be struggling with are things that they're going to really have to be working on.

83
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:33,000
 Oh yeah.

84
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:33,000
 Even movies.

85
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:39,000
 I mean, people have difficulties watching movies nowadays because I used to be so excited to go to the movies.

86
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:41,000
 I was like, yes, a three hour movie.

87
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:41,000
 Fantastic.

88
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:42,000
 Fantastic.

89
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:49,000
 No, we prefer like short form contents and everything because you know, you have to maintain your attention for two hours, three hours for a movie.

90
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:53,000
 And then like a big screen, like a big screen, like movie theater, like that's absolute focus.

91
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:59,000
 Whereas now like, Oh, I'll have a small, you know, home, home cinema, but also my cell phone and also have maybe something, my computer out.

92
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:09,000
 Like there'll be three screens going on and people, I mean, I, I love that selectivity of being able to choose what you want, but at the same time, there has to be a moment where there's an absolute, like there, there's an app, you know, like, like you go to mass.

93
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:11,000
 It's like, okay, it's phone turned off.

94
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:13,000
 I'm absolutely focused, uh, classroom.

95
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:15,000
 I'm absolutely focused on the professor cinema theater, whatever.

96
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:17,000
 Like I'm, I'm focused on the art form.

97
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:23,000
 Um, do you, um, father, what do you, where do you think?

98
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:27,000
 Cause I, I feel this is another thing I, I, I heard as I was preparing for this interview.

99
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:46,000
 Um, there were a lot of teachers and I think this is probably more in like primary school and secondary school education where the teachers also feel that because, um, the formation that happened that typically used to happen in the household, um, is not happening as much as it used to as, as, as families, you know, fracture.

100
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:52,000
 As, as, as kind of the, the kids coming from broken households, it's much more common.

101
00:07:52,000 --> 00:08:00,000
 Um, they, they say that they're, the teachers are having, are finding themselves having to do a lot of other things outside of just, you know, teaching mathematics or, or history class.

102
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:11,000
 And, and that of course then spirals into, you know, the, the, the, the issues surrounding cell phones, smartphones, all that stuff that kind of contribute to more pressure and anxiety on children.

103
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:17,000
 Isolation because what used to be a day at the park is now a day at home by yourself as we're all zooming in together doing, you know.

104
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:28,000
 Um, do you, do you, do you find that also at the graduate level and at the, at the university level that, that students are having by and large a more difficult time just focusing on the material?

105
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:29,000
 Yes, I think so.

106
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:30,000
 Right.

107
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:31,000
 Right.

108
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:32,000
 You're right.

109
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:34,000
 Because the family is supposed to be the first school.

110
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:35,000
 Right.

111
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:37,000
 The first place where you're, you get educated.

112
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:40,000
 You, you guys should explain how we live.

113
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:41,000
 Right.

114
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:42,000
 Right.

115
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:48,000
 And then there, there are so many people who don't obtain this first primary education and in the family, as you said.

116
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:49,000
 Right.

117
00:08:49,000 --> 00:09:00,000
 And yeah, I was going to jump into what you said earlier as well, that when we were in the period of COVID, right, we, we got really excited about this, all this online thing, right?

118
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:01,000
 Right.

119
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:03,000
 Oh, we can actually attend our classes online.

120
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:04,000
 Right.

121
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:06,000
 We can have this online session webinars and everything.

122
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:12,000
 Now it's me personally, I, I really, I don't despise online meetings, right?

123
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:17,000
 I don't despise online encounters, but I long for in-person events.

124
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:18,000
 Right.

125
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:26,000
 I think, uh, experience like, you know, COVID, I don't want to say it's good, but it teaches us a lot of things.

126
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:31,000
 It shows, manifests what we really value as human persons.

127
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:34,000
 Oh, we value this in-person encounters.

128
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:35,000
 Right.

129
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:38,000
 And this is very important in theology.

130
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:39,000
 Right.

131
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:41,000
 There's an expression actually in Italian.

132
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:43,000
 It's very descriptive of this.

133
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:45,000
 It's, this is not good.

134
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:46,000
 Okay.

135
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:48,000
 It's theologia fatta a tavolino.

136
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:49,000
 Fatta a tavolino.

137
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:53,000
 It's probably can be translated into English as office theology.

138
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:54,000
 Right.

139
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:56,000
 Like a theology done at an office, right?

140
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:57,000
 Sitting.

141
00:09:57,000 --> 00:09:59,000
 Probably you, you, you might look really hard working, right?

142
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:02,000
 You're thinking about one thing, but you're isolated.

143
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:05,000
 So you don't really value what's important.

144
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:09,000
 You don't have the scope and purview contacts or dialogue.

145
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:12,000
 It's more theory than, than anything actually real.

146
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:13,000
 Exactly.

147
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:14,000
 It's, it's theory, right?

148
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:15,000
 It's theory.

149
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:23,000
 But theology has always been done in the church, meaning in, in the community of Christians, right?

150
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:26,000
 It's done by talking to others.

151
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:28,000
 It's done by responding to other people's objections.

152
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:32,000
 It's done by, you know, public disputes in the medieval times.

153
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:34,000
 That's what theology is.

154
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:35,000
 You are in dialogue.

155
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:39,000
 You're in touch with people who are doing the same thing as well.

156
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:40,000
 Right.

157
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:44,000
 So we're always doing it as a community, never as an individual.

158
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:49,000
 That, that is interesting that, that you're saying as a community rather than an individual.

159
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:54,000
 I feel that one of the, one of the problems that I, I think of when I was going through

160
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:59,000
 my educational park course was that it was very much an individual pursuit.

161
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:00,000
 Okay.

162
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:02,000
 I was, I was under pressure to get good grades.

163
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:04,000
 I was under pressure to do extracurriculars.

164
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:08,000
 I was under pressure and it wasn't me versus my other classmates necessarily, but there was,

165
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:13,000
 I mean, and I think healthy competition is wonderful, but it was not at all me as a member of the community.

166
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:17,000
 I mean, it was very much, I need to go to a good school and I need to do whatever I can to get to a good school.

167
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:25,000
 And I know in my, in my class, like there was an enormous amount of students who had that, but it was, it was very much individually motivated.

168
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:31,000
 And I, and, and once again, like I think competition, healthy competition is great because it can make you strive to be your best.

169
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:35,000
 But I look at that and there's two things I would say about that.

170
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:39,000
 I wonder how we can get back to a communal aspect.

171
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:47,000
 And I think maybe one of the things that hurts that is that at least in the U S which I think is a good thing, but that people go far away to the colleges.

172
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:52,000
 Like, I mean, there are people who go to the state school just next door, but a lot of people have ambitions to go to the best schools.

173
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:54,000
 And they're oftentimes, you know, they're, they're far away.

174
00:11:54,000 --> 00:12:04,000
 But, but another aspect that I'm, that I'd be curious father to hear from you is, is, so what would that, what would a communal educational format look like where everyone is genuinely rooting for everyone?

175
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:07,000
 Um, rather than, okay, what can I get, you know, what can I, how can I get ahead?

176
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:13,000
 And also, um, when I was going to school, even though there was a lot of pressure, there was a level of optimism of, okay, cool.

177
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:15,000
 Well, I get to good college and then I'll get a good job.

178
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:17,000
 And, and, you know, the world is mine in a sense.

179
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:25,000
 And I feel now when I talk to some members of my family and some friends who have kids who are, you know, in that high school age, there isn't that same optimism.

180
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:33,000
 It's more, it feels more like a survival educational format where like, gosh, I just, I need to get a postdocs that maybe hopefully I can get a teaching position.

181
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:45,000
 Maybe if I'm lucky, or I need to do this thing so I can just barely sneak by, you know, I feel like there's a feeling, and I don't know father, if you feel the same thing, but there isn't that same optimism as there was maybe 10 years ago.

182
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:57,000
 And I wonder if this, the, the kind of the technological vision of, well, AI is just going to take all the jobs or, you know, some, some version of that, if, if that, if you feel that as well, or if you see that as well.

183
00:12:57,000 --> 00:12:59,000
 Yeah, I think so.

184
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:09,000
 In a sense, yeah, we forget sometimes that we, we study to know the truth, right?

185
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:15,000
 Truth is something to be pursued for, for its own sake, right?

186
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:23,000
 And, and I think we are acquiring unconsciously this utilitarian vision of education, right?

187
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:37,000
 Oh, I got to do this because I, and when this education does not guarantee me getting the, you know, objective, then I lose passion, I lose interest in education in itself, right?

188
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:43,000
 So I think, of course, we got to be very practical, we got to survive in the world, get a job and everything, right?

189
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:56,000
 So I think it's a good balance that we have to try to seek between, you know, okay, I know that I learned because as a human person, I was created by God to know the truth, right?

190
00:13:56,000 --> 00:14:02,000
 That's one of the basic human instincts, Thomas Aquinas says it, and then we want to know the truth.

191
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:04,000
 Nobody likes being lied to, right?

192
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:08,000
 And that's a basic human instinct, like looking for food, right?

193
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:11,000
 Personal survival, survival of the species, etc.

194
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:13,000
 So we want to know the truth.

195
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:15,000
 And that's why I learned.

196
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:19,000
 Now, our grading system sometimes is not very helpful, is it?

197
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:22,000
 So there's a lot to say about this, right?

198
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:25,000
 I read an article not a very long time ago about ungrading.

199
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:32,000
 So an author, I think in the States, if I'm not mistaken, is proposing ungrading, right?

200
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:33,000
 Not grading your students.

201
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:38,000
 Instead, we can let them decide the grade they want at the beginning of the course.

202
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:44,000
 And then the task of the teacher is to help that student achieve that grade.

203
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:45,000
 So I want to get a B, right?

204
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:47,000
 Oh, I want to get an A.

205
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:48,000
 Then, okay, let me help you.

206
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:54,000
 So if that student, the teacher says that, oh, you get a B, you wanted an A, but you get a B.

207
00:14:54,000 --> 00:15:00,000
 It's not like I'm punishing you, but you could have done a little bit more to achieve your goal, right?

208
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:01,000
 You wanted an A, right?

209
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:03,000
 So it's like helping the students.

210
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:07,000
 It's a great idea, I think, in an ideal world, right?

211
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:12,000
 In our current world, well, at least we have systems in place, et cetera.

212
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:25,000
 But I think all teachers, every teacher can at least do something in order to focus the grading, not on the result, but on the process.

213
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:30,000
 So education or learning a course, right?

214
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:35,000
 A university course, for example, is getting from point A to point B, right?

215
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:36,000
 Okay, okay.

216
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:37,000
 What's the objective here?

217
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:42,000
 Okay, I want to help my students know the Trinity better, right?

218
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:44,000
 That's the goal, right?

219
00:15:44,000 --> 00:15:45,000
 Know the Trinity better.

220
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:54,000
 And then not only know it conceptually or academically, if you want, but also know how knowing the Trinity better.

221
00:15:54,000 --> 00:16:01,000
 Can change your life, change your prayer life, change your social life as well.

222
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:02,000
 So that's the goal.

223
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:06,000
 And then getting from point A to point B is where I want to grade, right?

224
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:07,000
 Okay.

225
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:08,000
 How are you progressing in this?

226
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:13,000
 Now, this is very abstract and, you know, every person is different.

227
00:16:13,000 --> 00:16:17,000
 So I think dedicating time to every student is also important.

228
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:24,000
 And this is where, at least I try to shift my methodology to this direction.

229
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:39,000
 And Father, do you think as, you know, I mean, hopefully with, you know, with AI, teachers will be able to dedicate more time to their students with, you know, busy work, admin, admin stuff, streamlining some of those tasks with AI.

230
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:46,000
 We hope at least that AI is going to permit them so that the teachers can shine a light more on the students needs.

231
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:53,000
 Do you, on the practical level today, do you, how are you using AI?

232
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:59,000
 Are you finding it being a useful tool to streamline those tasks so that you can dedicate more time to the students?

233
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:00,000
 Of course.

234
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:01,000
 Of course.

235
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:02,000
 Of course.

236
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:03,000
 Yeah.

237
00:17:03,000 --> 00:17:05,000
 I guess I use AI every day for different things.

238
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:09,000
 For translating something, for example, that's a task I use AI for, right?

239
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:14,000
 Because it does quite a good job in translating texts, right?

240
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:19,000
 Or writing emails to students or to colleagues and everything.

241
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:25,000
 You know, drafting a good email is just as important as having an important message, right?

242
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:30,000
 Because when an email is ambiguous, it's not clear, then people will be asking you again.

243
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:33,000
 And it's a lot of back and forth that really consumes your time.

244
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:38,000
 So I use AI for that as well for a lot of just administrative tasks, right?

245
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:41,000
 And then dividing my students into groups, right?

246
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:47,000
 Or, and then for proofreading as well, AI is, I find it useful for proofreading texts.

247
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:51,000
 Before you might pay somebody to do it for you, right?

248
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:54,000
 Or, but now you have AI to help you with it.

249
00:17:54,000 --> 00:17:58,000
 And it's very helpful in this direction, I think.

250
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:05,000
 And then, as you said, it helps me dedicate time for students in ways I did less before.

251
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:16,000
 And then, Father, there's kind of the stresses that I've read and I've spoken to a few teachers around AI of the authenticity of the work.

252
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:25,000
 So, you know, people wondering, okay, well, the college essay was a standard, you know, assignment that would be assigned to almost every student, regardless of the classes they're taking.

253
00:18:25,000 --> 00:18:36,000
 And they're going to be doing several, you know, college essays per term, history, English, you know, ethics, you know, theology.

254
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:41,000
 With ChatGPT, for example, professors have talked about, okay, well, how do we, how do we catch for plagiarism?

255
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:51,000
 How do we, you know, help students really do that hard work of doing the research for the paper, learning sentence structures, really making a good argument?

256
00:18:51,000 --> 00:18:58,000
 How are you and your colleagues handling essay formats like in this age of AI?

257
00:18:58,000 --> 00:18:59,000
 Right.

258
00:18:59,000 --> 00:19:03,000
 Yeah, we had a discussion about this not a very long time ago.

259
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:08,000
 Me and my colleagues said that the faculty, right, this is a very pressing problem, I think.

260
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:15,000
 On the one hand, we are convinced that we are not teaching our students to do what AI can do better.

261
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:16,000
 Right.

262
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:18,000
 That's important to say, right?

263
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:24,000
 Because, okay, I don't want to teach my students to do better what, to do what AI could do better.

264
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:27,000
 So, at least this is what I do, right?

265
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:32,000
 There are different approaches and I might be wrong as well, I might change this next year, right?

266
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:35,000
 But at least this year, I do not assign papers.

267
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:39,000
 Because as you said, we can generate papers using artificial intelligence.

268
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:43,000
 Instead, I focus more on oral exams, right?

269
00:19:43,000 --> 00:19:49,000
 On tutorial groups where students will get together with myself as well.

270
00:19:49,000 --> 00:19:55,000
 And then I will try to stimulate debates, discussions.

271
00:19:55,000 --> 00:20:04,000
 And hopefully this tutorial groups will also be their study groups, maybe, right, if they find themselves at ease.

272
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:10,000
 So, it's shifting the focus to what's more in person, more direct, right, immediate.

273
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:13,000
 To non-mediated formats of exams.

274
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:15,000
 At the same time, though.

275
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:20,000
 So, we cannot ditch writing as if it's not important, right?

276
00:20:20,000 --> 00:20:24,000
 So, okay, I don't assign papers, but I'm not saying that, okay, forget about writing.

277
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:25,000
 No.

278
00:20:25,000 --> 00:20:29,000
 Because, for me, myself at least, writing is thinking, right?

279
00:20:29,000 --> 00:20:30,000
 For me, too.

280
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:31,000
 For me, too.

281
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:32,000
 Yeah, right?

282
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:34,000
 So, when I write, I think.

283
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:35,000
 Yeah.

284
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:37,000
 And to think, I need to write.

285
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:38,000
 Yeah.

286
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:39,000
 I need to talk out loud.

287
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:40,000
 I need to think.

288
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:41,000
 I need to write.

289
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:42,000
 It's a circle.

290
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:45,000
 And then the thought becomes better as you write it down.

291
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:46,000
 Because then it becomes real.

292
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:48,000
 And you're like, oh, that's not exactly what I meant.

293
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:49,000
 How do you change it?

294
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:50,000
 Exactly.

295
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:53,000
 I think it's a very important part of the process.

296
00:20:53,000 --> 00:20:55,000
 And then, Father, just to jump on that.

297
00:20:55,000 --> 00:20:59,000
 And this might be, you know, almost an impossible question in the sense that I've been thinking

298
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:00,000
 about it a lot.

299
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:03,000
 Is, what is the difference?

300
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:08,000
 So, I mean, I agree that you're teaching students to do something different than an artificial

301
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:12,000
 intelligence can just replicate or give the simulation of intelligence.

302
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:18,000
 But what, in your mind, what is the difference between human knowledge, which of course is earned

303
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:23,000
 and worked for and that whole process, versus something that seems like a simulation of it.

304
00:21:23,000 --> 00:21:26,000
 Like, you know, an artificial, you know, intelligence in that sense.

305
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:27,000
 Like, what is the difference?

306
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:30,000
 Because I think that that's where the fault line, of course, is.

307
00:21:30,000 --> 00:21:34,000
 Where what you are doing is very different than what can be simply reproduced.

308
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:36,000
 Well, there's a lot to say about this.

309
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:43,000
 We can draw from, you know, ancient philosophy, Aristotle, Plato, and from Christian philosophy as well.

310
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:48,000
 But probably this one word that can summarize this, I think, quite well.

311
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:54,000
 It's the fact that our intelligence is embodied.

312
00:21:54,000 --> 00:22:00,000
 So, we're not just spirits like flying around, but we're body and soul, right?

313
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:01,000
 Unity of body and soul.

314
00:22:01,000 --> 00:22:03,000
 That's what a human being is.

315
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:06,000
 And my intelligence is embodied.

316
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:10,000
 So, the way I know is through the senses.

317
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:11,000
 I see something.

318
00:22:11,000 --> 00:22:13,000
 I perceive something, right?

319
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:14,000
 I hear something.

320
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:20,000
 And then I abstract from what I earned from my senses a concept, right?

321
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:22,000
 That helps me know the reality.

322
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:25,000
 That's the way human thinking, human intelligence works.

323
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:27,000
 And AI is not embodied.

324
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:29,000
 So, it's never experienced.

325
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:30,000
 It's never touched anything, right?

326
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:33,000
 It's never scraped its knees and all that.

327
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:34,000
 So, it's embodied.

328
00:22:34,000 --> 00:22:37,000
 And therefore, human intelligence is also relational.

329
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:45,000
 And the way I know something is through relationships with things, with persons, with people, right?

330
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:50,000
 So, AI is good at so many things.

331
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:55,000
 But I think it's not quite good at unpredictable circumstances, right?

332
00:22:55,000 --> 00:22:58,000
 That requires creativity, immediate responses.

333
00:22:58,000 --> 00:23:02,000
 And you see all those self-driving cars, right?

334
00:23:02,000 --> 00:23:07,000
 And you can read on the internet what happened to those self-driving cars, right?

335
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:09,000
 When they park.

336
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:14,000
 Why a human driver is still better than self-driving cars?

337
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:19,000
 If it were not, then we would have had self-driving cars anywhere, right?

338
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:20,000
 Everywhere.

339
00:23:20,000 --> 00:23:27,000
 But it's the capability to respond to a myriad of situations, unpredictable situations, that human being.

340
00:23:27,000 --> 00:23:28,000
 Why?

341
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:30,000
 Because we have experienced it.

342
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:33,000
 Because our knowledge is embodied.

343
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:38,000
 And Father, what do you think we lose by using ChatGPT every day?

344
00:23:38,000 --> 00:23:42,000
 Do you think there's something that the average, you know, student is losing?

345
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:45,000
 A critical, you know, learning experience?

346
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:56,000
 I wonder about this often, as I see also in my personal life, you know, using these AI tools more and more often for mundane tasks.

347
00:23:56,000 --> 00:24:02,000
 But I wonder, you know, when I was in undergrad, I didn't have, you know, an AI.

348
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:08,000
 And so every paper I wrote, and that was, I know that there was value in that.

349
00:24:08,000 --> 00:24:13,000
 And I wonder with these young students, as more and more technological tools, which are tools, which means there's lots of good.

350
00:24:13,000 --> 00:24:24,000
 But as that, as that, those opportunities and those options are made available, it becomes harder and harder to say, well, I'm not going to take that, you know, that opportunity to do something quicker or do something more efficiently.

351
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:25,000
 Right.

352
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:31,000
 I think there's something one loses when one is heavily reliant on AI tools.

353
00:24:31,000 --> 00:24:36,000
 First one is this artisanal aspect of thinking.

354
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:37,000
 Right.

355
00:24:37,000 --> 00:24:38,000
 Right.

356
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:42,000
 When we use AI to, for example, let's say, draft an email, right?

357
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:45,000
 Or write something up.

358
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:48,000
 Yeah, you get from point A to point B, right?

359
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:50,000
 Getting the email done and sent.

360
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:52,000
 But then you haven't gone through it.

361
00:24:52,000 --> 00:24:55,000
 It's not something, it's not embodied, right?

362
00:24:55,000 --> 00:24:56,000
 Yeah.

363
00:24:56,000 --> 00:25:00,000
 It's like, okay, I want to, we talked about, like, walking or jogging earlier.

364
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:01,000
 Yeah, yeah, yeah.

365
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:13,000
 Okay, I want to get my steps in, but I'm just going to drive from, you know, here to Santa Maria Maggiore and then, I don't know, turn on the app or something and let it register it as my steps, right?

366
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:17,000
 I get my steps in, but I haven't walked those steps, right?

367
00:25:17,000 --> 00:25:18,000
 Those miles.

368
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:20,000
 So I think it's similar, right?

369
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:22,000
 Or riding a bike or anything.

370
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:23,000
 We can find all sorts of analogies.

371
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:25,000
 So the first is, okay, it's not embodied.

372
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:26,000
 You haven't done it.

373
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:38,000
 That's why, at least, I try every day to dedicate certain time to unaided writing, unaided thinking.

374
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:41,000
 I don't use Gemini or HGPD or anything.

375
00:25:41,000 --> 00:25:42,000
 I write.

376
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:44,000
 I write the old school way.

377
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:48,000
 Just type, I mean, type or, you know, better even if we can write, right?

378
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:49,000
 Handwrite.

379
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:56,000
 I just type with, probably with errors, with, you know, I just type, but this helps me think, right?

380
00:25:56,000 --> 00:26:01,000
 And there's the second thing we lose as well, if we are heavily dependent on AI tools.

381
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:08,000
 I think it's our humanity or the human character of our products.

382
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:11,000
 It's like when reading emails, I can sense.

383
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:16,000
 I don't want to say I can know like a hundred percent of this is AI generated or not.

384
00:26:16,000 --> 00:26:20,000
 But when an email contains a small error, now I rejoice in it.

385
00:26:20,000 --> 00:26:23,000
 It's like when I receive an email with a small error, right?

386
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:29,000
 Oh, this person has put a time into writing the email without the aid of AI, right?

387
00:26:29,000 --> 00:26:31,000
 I'm, I'm, I'm valued.

388
00:26:31,000 --> 00:26:36,000
 I'm, I work his time, right?

389
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:38,000
 Before I was like, I'm boo, this typo, right?

390
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:40,000
 And now I, I marvel at it.

391
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:41,000
 I mean, wow.

392
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:42,000
 I marvel at it.

393
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:44,000
 And people write with errors, right?

394
00:26:44,000 --> 00:26:45,000
 Absolutely.

395
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:47,000
 And they think with errors and they, they've talked with errors.

396
00:26:47,000 --> 00:26:49,000
 Radical errors here and there, right?

397
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:50,000
 It's fine.

398
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:56,000
 And I mean, it's not fine, but you know, it's, it's, it demonstrates humanity, right?

399
00:26:56,000 --> 00:27:02,000
 And when the emails are perfect, but it's, it's written with, without AI, I can sense

400
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:04,000
 it as well because the language it uses, right?

401
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:10,000
 The variety of verbs used in the email or, or writings, we can apply this to articles,

402
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:11,000
 right?

403
00:27:11,000 --> 00:27:12,000
 So our humanity.

404
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:13,000
 Yeah.

405
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:17,000
 And then father, I wanted to ask him when you're, when you're talking to your students

406
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:20,000
 and when you're teaching a class and you mentioned, you know, that it's quite international

407
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:24,000
 often, um, what do you notice about different students from different parts of the world?

408
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:26,000
 Are the, is the format of education different?

409
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:28,000
 Is the work ethic different?

410
00:27:28,000 --> 00:27:31,000
 Is, um, the attention to certain tasks different?

411
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:35,000
 Like what, what makes, you know, a student from a Roman student and Italian student here,

412
00:27:35,000 --> 00:27:39,000
 who's, you know, studying to be a priest, a seminarian, uh, in your class different from,

413
00:27:39,000 --> 00:27:44,000
 let's say someone from the United States, from, from North Africa, from, from Asia, you

414
00:27:44,000 --> 00:27:49,000
 know, what, what do you see in the, in the educational history, you know, and the traditions

415
00:27:49,000 --> 00:27:51,000
 of education as being different or as markers?

416
00:27:51,000 --> 00:27:54,000
 I'll generalize a lot, I think.

417
00:27:54,000 --> 00:28:00,000
 But yeah, but that's a great question because every geographical area has its own idiosyncrasies,

418
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:01,000
 right?

419
00:28:01,000 --> 00:28:03,000
 In, in learning and approaching education.

420
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:07,000
 I think in, at least in Europe, this is a broad strokes, right?

421
00:28:07,000 --> 00:28:16,000
 In Europe, the, um, students are used to this lecture style where very, you know, magisterial.

422
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:17,000
 I mean, right?

423
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:20,000
 It's like, okay, teach a frontal classes.

424
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:21,000
 We call it in Italian, right?

425
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:26,000
 It's like face to face and the teacher talking, exposing, right?

426
00:28:26,000 --> 00:28:27,000
 The whole thing.

427
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:34,000
 Well, what I like about the education in the States is that the students have to be active

428
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:35,000
 as well.

429
00:28:35,000 --> 00:28:37,000
 They have to put in something, right?

430
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:42,000
 So they're more used to discussion formats, right?

431
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:43,000
 Group works.

432
00:28:43,000 --> 00:28:45,000
 And then probably presentation.

433
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:48,000
 Oh, this is a little bit less common in Europe.

434
00:28:48,000 --> 00:28:53,000
 I noticed that because I remember I took a class here and, um, it was a philosophy class

435
00:28:53,000 --> 00:28:57,000
 because I adore philosophy and it was completely lecture based.

436
00:28:57,000 --> 00:29:00,000
 And I found it very tedious, even though the professor was wonderful.

437
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:01,000
 I was antsy.

438
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:04,000
 And I remember, uh, in undergrad and graduate school.

439
00:29:04,000 --> 00:29:08,000
 And of course in high school in the U S very projects based, you know, okay.

440
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:11,000
 The professor gives it, or the teacher gives a, gives an opening statement and then, okay,

441
00:29:11,000 --> 00:29:13,000
 break off into small groups, come back with something.

442
00:29:13,000 --> 00:29:17,000
 And I, and I love that creative kind of entrepreneurial aspect.

443
00:29:17,000 --> 00:29:18,000
 Oh yeah.

444
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:20,000
 It's more, more dynamic, right?

